## 🧠 Concept 3: Offline-First Mobile (THE BIG ONE)

### What it means
Your mobile app should work **without internet**. The user should be able to:
- View their grocery items, categories, shopping lists
- Add/edit/delete items
- Mark items as purchased

All **without** any server connection. Then, when internet comes back, everything syncs.

### How it works — the "Local-First" pattern

```mermaid
graph LR
    subgraph "Phone (Flutter App)"
        UI["UI Screens"]
        REPO["Repository Layer"]
        LOCAL[("SQLite<br/>Local DB")]
        SYNC["Sync Engine"]
    end
    
    subgraph "Server"
        API["Express API"]
        REMOTE[("MySQL<br/>Central DB")]
    end
    
    UI --> REPO
    REPO --> LOCAL
    SYNC -->|"Pull changes"| API
    SYNC -->|"Push changes"| API
    API --> REMOTE
    SYNC <-->|"Read/Write"| LOCAL
```

**The key idea:** Your UI **never** talks to the server directly. It always reads/writes to the **local SQLite database**. A separate **Sync Engine** runs in the background and keeps the local DB in sync with the server.

### Why this pattern?
| Scenario | Without offline-first | With offline-first |
|---|---|---|
| No internet | ❌ App shows errors/blank | ✅ Everything works |
| Slow internet | ⏳ UI freezes waiting | ✅ Instant, syncs in background |
| Add item offline | ❌ Fails | ✅ Saved locally, synced later |
| Open app on subway | ❌ Nothing loads | ✅ Shows last synced data |

