## 🧠 Concept 4: Sync — How Changes Flow

### The Problem
If someone adds an item from the **web** while the phone is offline, how does the phone know about it later?

### The Solution: Timestamp-Based Sync

Every record in the database gets two new columns:
- `updated_at` — when was this record last modified?
- `is_deleted` — was this record deleted? (we never truly delete, we "soft delete")

The mobile app remembers: *"The last time I synced was at 2024-01-15 10:30:00"*

When it comes online, it asks the server: *"Give me everything that changed after 2024-01-15 10:30:00"*

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Phone as 📱 Mobile App
    participant Server as 🖥️ Express API
    participant DB as 🗄️ MySQL

    Note over Phone: Comes online after being offline

    Phone->>Server: GET /api/sync/pull?since=2024-01-15T10:30:00
    Server->>DB: SELECT * WHERE updated_at > '2024-01-15T10:30:00' AND user_id = 5
    DB-->>Server: Changed categories, items, lists...
    Server-->>Phone: {categories: [...], masterItems: [...], ...}
    
    Note over Phone: Also has local changes made while offline
    
    Phone->>Server: POST /api/sync/push {changes: [...]}
    Server->>DB: INSERT/UPDATE each change
    Server-->>Phone: {ok: true, serverVersions: [...]}
    
    Note over Phone: Updates local "last_synced" timestamp
```

### What about conflicts?
If the **same item** was edited on both web and mobile while offline, we need a rule. The simplest and most practical rule for a grocery app:

> **Last Write Wins** — whichever change has the later `updated_at` timestamp wins.

This is simple, predictable, and perfectly fine for a grocery app (you're not editing legal documents here!).

