#### [NEW] [repository.dart](file:///c:/Users/raksh/Desktop/GrocerySho_List/frontend_mobile/lib/data/repository.dart)

The **Repository Pattern** — this is the single layer your UI talks to. The screens never call `ApiService` or `LocalDatabase` directly. They call `Repository`, which decides what to do.

```dart
class Repository {
  // UI calls this — it always reads from local SQLite (instant!)
  Future<List<Category>> getCategories() => localDb.getCategories();
  
  // UI calls this — saves to local SQLite, marks as dirty
  Future<void> addCategory(String name) {
    localDb.insertCategory(name, isDirty: true);
    syncEngine.triggerSync(); // try to sync if online
  }
}
```

**Why a repository?** It decouples your UI from the data source. Your screens don't care if data comes from SQLite, the server, or magic. They just call `repository.getCategories()`. This makes your code much cleaner and easier to test.

